    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-22T13:40:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-22T13:40:00-05:00" n="274"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d274">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 839.00/1105.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Sullivan</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegrams.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>
                            <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Santo Domingo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-22T14:00:00-04:40">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 22, 1914, 2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>As elections approach country in feverish state. Arias uniting with various
                    opposition groups. All outs now assailing Bordas party. Much hostility towards
                    American Government and myself. We are accused of failing in our promises. Arias
                    published my request contained in your instruction of March 1, 4 p.m., with
                    defiant refusal. Systematic press attacks upon Legation are, I believe, inspired
                    by old grafting ring taking advantage of excitement. Provisional Government has
                    insisted as result of rumored plot upon placing guards day and night around
                    Legation. All parties preparing for polls. Bitter protests from Arias’ faction
                    on removal of Arias’ Governors in [north?]. Arias unquestionably intends to be
                    President of the Republic but is now ostensibly supporting Jimenez. His success
                    would mean chaos and plunder. On the other hand Provisional Government chafes at
                    reprisals and is eager to employ boot and spur policy. I am insisting upon
                    Provisional Government’s obligation to give country decent election.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sullivan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
